WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.080 --> 00:00:05.120
SARAH THOMSON: Hello, everybody.

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:07.260
Good morning.

00:00:07.260 --> 00:00:10.370
My name is Sarah, and for
the last 2 and 1/2 years

00:00:10.370 --> 00:00:13.730
I've been heading up the indie
community on Google Play,

00:00:13.730 --> 00:00:15.660
and it's been an
awesome experience.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:20.300
I started as an indie myself
well over 10 years ago,

00:00:20.300 --> 00:00:23.150
and it's still my
favorite group of people.

00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:24.860
I'm a little bit
biased with indies,

00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:27.290
so you'll probably
see that come through

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:30.680
as I talk to these
two amazing humans.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:32.720
And this morning we
talked a lot about-- we

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:35.720
had some great talks
run by Googlers

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:38.750
and some of our partners who
were talking about improving

00:00:38.750 --> 00:00:41.630
game quality, and how
can you really maximize

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:42.990
your discoverability.

00:00:42.990 --> 00:00:44.960
And we're going to
actually kick off

00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:48.860
into a lot of different
discussions carrying on

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:50.670
to build on top of that.

00:00:50.670 --> 00:00:55.370
So today I have Sam and Mike,
who are two indie developers

00:00:55.370 --> 00:00:59.780
and publisher, who are
really experts and have seen

00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:03.290
a lot of success around user
acquisition, which is something

00:01:03.290 --> 00:01:05.600
that I think a lot of
indies really struggle with.

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:08.850
Put your hand up if you
struggle with user acquisition--

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:12.230
like, where to even
start, what is it.

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:13.770
It's super overwhelming.

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:18.020
And then we also have
Butterscotch Shenanigans here,

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:20.810
which are experts around
community-building.

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:23.005
So we're going to talk
about those two things.

00:01:23.005 --> 00:01:24.980
It's going to be super exciting.

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:25.480
All right.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:26.022
Welcome guys.

00:01:26.022 --> 00:01:26.938
Thanks for joining us.

00:01:26.938 --> 00:01:27.730
SAM COSTER: Thanks.

00:01:27.730 --> 00:01:30.670
SARAH THOMSON: So maybe let's
start with some introductions.

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:31.810
Sam, maybe you can start.

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:33.350
Talk a little bit
about yourself,

00:01:33.350 --> 00:01:36.322
your history in gaming,
about your company, so forth.

00:01:36.322 --> 00:01:37.030
SAM COSTER: Sure.

00:01:37.030 --> 00:01:37.530
Yeah.

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:40.390
So Butterscotch Shenanigans was
founded about seven years ago

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:42.190
by me and my two brothers.

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:44.850
And a family-owned business,
which is always a terrible idea

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:47.060
I've heard, but it's
working out pretty good.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:48.790
And we've launched five games.

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:51.010
We started on mobile
and we've recently

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:53.315
gone more cross-platform,
so our games now

00:01:53.315 --> 00:01:54.940
reach out onto other
platforms as well,

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:56.313
like Steam and console.

00:01:56.313 --> 00:01:57.730
And a big part of
our strategy has

00:01:57.730 --> 00:02:00.010
been answering the
question, once we somehow

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:02.560
manage to get a
player, how can we

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:04.030
just keep that player around?

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:06.235
So instead of worrying
about user acquisition

00:02:06.235 --> 00:02:08.110
in terms of bringing
new people in, how do we

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:08.991
keep people with us.

00:02:08.991 --> 00:02:10.949
And that's sort of been
what a lot of our focus

00:02:10.949 --> 00:02:12.630
is, around community management
and that sort of thing.

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:13.646
MIKE GORDON: Cool.

00:02:13.646 --> 00:02:14.490
I'm Mike.

00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:16.510
I'm the CEO of Iron Horse Games.

00:02:16.510 --> 00:02:19.450
There's one person at Iron
Horse Games, and that's me.

00:02:19.450 --> 00:02:23.750
I started the company
three years ago.

00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:28.180
Last year we did 11
million installs,

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:30.550
with a heavy amount
of user acquisition.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:33.670
So I do a lot of
marketing myself,

00:02:33.670 --> 00:02:36.430
a lot of creative
testing, and mostly

00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:38.270
focus on Idle Game publishing.

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:39.200
That's it.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:40.340
SARAH THOMSON: Cool.

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:43.360
So the first obvious question I
want to ask you is, why indie?

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:46.570
Why did you choose to
be an indie developer?

00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:49.360
I think a lot of people
feel it's harder than ever

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:52.240
to be indie, especially
in mobile and increasingly

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.600
on other platforms.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:56.370
Why did you choose this path?

00:02:56.370 --> 00:02:57.120
MIKE GORDON: Sure.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:59.000
I can start.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.540
It's personal and professional.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:03.455
So personally, I had worked
at Kongregate previously

00:03:03.455 --> 00:03:05.580
and helped build up the
mobile publishing business.

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:08.063
We'd worked with a lot
of really big teams,

00:03:08.063 --> 00:03:10.230
and I wanted to get more
hands-on with smaller teams

00:03:10.230 --> 00:03:11.860
and make an impact
on their games.

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:14.340
And that's been personally
really satisfying.

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:16.080
Professionally, I
saw that there was

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:19.290
a big gap in the market from
a publishing perspective.

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:20.790
From a business
perspective, the way

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:23.250
that publishing typically
works if you have success

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:24.540
is you build on that success.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:27.618
You have a game, it generates
a lot of money, you market it,

00:03:27.618 --> 00:03:29.910
and then start hiring on a
team to help build the games

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:32.040
bigger, which means that
subsequent games need

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:33.180
to be bigger and bigger.

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.140
And that creates
a snowball effect,

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:36.690
and then you look
up after four years

00:03:36.690 --> 00:03:38.910
and you're publishing
like two games a year.

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:41.040
I never wanted to
do that, and felt

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:43.860
that there was a huge
opportunity for one

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:46.048
and two-person teams
to really benefit

00:03:46.048 --> 00:03:48.090
from a lot of the learnings
that the big team had

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:48.930
from publishing.

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:52.062
So that's what I set out to
do, and largely what I've done.

00:03:52.062 --> 00:03:53.020
SARAH THOMSON: Awesome.

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:53.728
SAM COSTER: Yeah.

00:03:53.728 --> 00:03:56.550
So on our end, one is that
we really like to make games.

00:03:56.550 --> 00:03:58.460
In the past we liked
to make them fast.

00:03:58.460 --> 00:03:59.730
That's changed a bit.

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:01.890
But we started out
doing game jams,

00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:03.390
and so that sort
of creative freedom

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:05.682
you get from just iterating
over a weekend we basically

00:04:05.682 --> 00:04:08.620
extended into how we
make our games generally.

00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:11.370
So we have a really iterative
design and development cycle.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:14.340
And on top of that,
the sort of new thing

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:16.148
that we do at our
studio is a lot

00:04:16.148 --> 00:04:17.940
of this really interesting
web tech and web

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:19.930
integration with our games.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:21.690
So we built our own
proprietary account

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:23.280
system called Bscotch
ID, which is now

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:25.760
transitioned into Rumpus,
which is our "powerful back

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:27.086
end," as we call it.

00:04:27.086 --> 00:04:27.657
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:27.657 --> 00:04:29.490
And what that allows
us to do is get players

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:33.000
into this email system, which
now we have half a million

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.383
players who have at some
point bought one of our games

00:04:35.383 --> 00:04:37.050
who we actually have
their email address

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:39.410
and we send them emails
basically once a month letting

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:40.450
them know what's
going on at the studio

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:43.080
as well as essentially hyping
up whatever our new game is

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:44.590
or selling merch
or whatever else.

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:46.143
So a big part of
our learnings have

00:04:46.143 --> 00:04:47.310
come on that side of things.

00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:49.268
We really wanted to have
the time and the space

00:04:49.268 --> 00:04:50.940
to explore that
whole aspect of it

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:52.600
and see what we could do there.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:54.600
SARAH THOMSON:
That's super cool.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:58.926
So Mike, I'm going to move
over to you and dive into--

00:04:58.926 --> 00:05:00.790
you come from gaming.

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:02.020
You're not new to games.

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:05.530
But being in this space of
really being this one-man indie

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:09.490
sensation, what's that been
like over the last few years?

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:10.990
What's the learning
curve been like?

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:11.170
MIKE GORDON: Yeah.

00:05:11.170 --> 00:05:13.430
So it's nice that you called me
a sensation, because it's not--

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:13.750
SARAH THOMSON: Yes.

00:05:13.750 --> 00:05:14.730
You are a sensation.

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:15.640
You are sensational.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:17.500
MIKE GORDON: Thank you.

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:20.740
It's been difficult and good.

00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:22.960
I think you can
probably relate to this.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:25.420
If you have any
degree of success

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:27.220
you start feeling a
little bit nervous

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:29.680
that it's going to go away.

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:32.172
So that's one
element that I deal

00:05:32.172 --> 00:05:33.880
with quite a bit,
especially when we have

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:36.070
a successful business, is
the feeling that it's not

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:39.490
going to be that way forever,
so you stay really scrappy.

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:43.150
I think the most important
learnings of the past three

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:47.050
years have really been the need
to adapt and do it quickly.

00:05:47.050 --> 00:05:49.450
When I started Iron
Horse Games, about a year

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:51.840
later the app store
did its redesign.

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:53.590
If anyone here is a
mobile game developer,

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:57.250
you've probably seen what
the impacts of that are.

00:05:57.250 --> 00:05:59.320
And then also there
have been a series

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:05.200
of changes on Google Play where
a lot of organic installs that

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.180
used to kind of
fall from the sky

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.135
have changed how they
come into your game.

00:06:09.135 --> 00:06:10.510
They're all still
there, you just

00:06:10.510 --> 00:06:12.177
have to figure out a
way to unlock them.

00:06:12.177 --> 00:06:15.340
For me it was leaning really
heavily into marketing and user

00:06:15.340 --> 00:06:16.360
acquisition.

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:19.480
So when those things
happen you need to pivot,

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:21.822
and you need to do it
incredibly quickly,

00:06:21.822 --> 00:06:23.530
because otherwise
you're going to wake up

00:06:23.530 --> 00:06:25.197
and you're not going
to have a business.

00:06:25.197 --> 00:06:28.030
I mean, if I didn't make the
changes that I made to start

00:06:28.030 --> 00:06:29.920
marketing aggressively
last year--

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:34.280
and I had done zero marketing
at Iron Horse before this--

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:36.260
I wouldn't be here today.

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:36.760
Period.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:37.968
The business would not exist.

00:06:37.968 --> 00:06:38.802
SARAH THOMSON: Yeah.

00:06:38.802 --> 00:06:40.930
So building off of
that and in reference

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:43.190
to what we were talking
about a little bit earlier,

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:49.300
is that you have really taken
on head-on the concept of user

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:49.990
acquisition.

00:06:49.990 --> 00:06:52.440
And how you started
from square one--

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:54.520
you really didn't
know much about it,

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:57.752
and now you've acquired this
incredible wealth of knowledge

00:06:57.752 --> 00:06:58.335
in that space.

00:06:58.335 --> 00:07:00.202
So how do you do
that as an indie?

00:07:00.202 --> 00:07:01.660
Where did you even
start with that?

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:02.410
MIKE GORDON: Yeah.

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:05.290
So, credit to Kongregate
and my time there because--

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:07.563
well, I wasn't actively
doing marketing myself.

00:07:07.563 --> 00:07:08.980
I was working with
that team a lot

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:12.190
and kind of getting an idea
of what that looked like.

00:07:12.190 --> 00:07:15.753
For the specific way that
I started doing marketing

00:07:15.753 --> 00:07:17.170
and started tackling
it, the first

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.822
was algorithm change
rolled through Google Play.

00:07:19.822 --> 00:07:22.030
Some of my games lost installs
and a lot of the games

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:22.900
kept them.

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:27.220
So I looked at why the
games who still had installs

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:28.830
were continuing to get them.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:30.580
The answer, at least
for me, was that they

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:33.033
had a high third-party
referral rate.

00:07:33.033 --> 00:07:34.450
So I was getting
a lot of installs

00:07:34.450 --> 00:07:35.617
from outside of Google Play.

00:07:35.617 --> 00:07:38.470
I inferred that that meant
that the algorithm might

00:07:38.470 --> 00:07:42.470
be encouraging developers
to market their games,

00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:44.740
so I started marketing
really conservatively

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:47.400
to start on live games.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:50.710
I'd take about 30% of
the projected net revenue

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:54.070
for the month, I would reinvest
that into marketing and user

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:55.690
acquisition through
sources that I

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:59.200
was confident would have
either net neutral--

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:02.622
so I wouldn't lose any money on
them-- or ROI positive payback.

00:08:02.622 --> 00:08:04.080
I mean, this is
not a lot of spend.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:06.730
We're talking like
$1,000 a month.

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:09.010
I monitor the results,
and then as that

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:11.590
started gaining
success and snowballing

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:15.070
I developed a strategy
around marketing on open beta

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:17.500
and then marketing during
launch, which is probably

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:20.170
the most important window
that you can market

00:08:20.170 --> 00:08:21.850
your game in on Google Play.

00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:26.170
So the first 30 days when you
release your game globally

00:08:26.170 --> 00:08:29.830
from open beta or
pre-registration,

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:33.470
the paid to organic
ratios are insane.

00:08:33.470 --> 00:08:37.090
Like, normally on a game
that's live maybe you

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:40.990
buy one install on Google
Play and you get one organic.

00:08:40.990 --> 00:08:43.690
During that launch window,
you buy one install

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:45.830
and you get four organics.

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:48.463
So knowing how to
market your game

00:08:48.463 --> 00:08:50.380
and having some experience
marketing your game

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:53.770
and then aggressively marketing
during that 30-day window

00:08:53.770 --> 00:08:56.290
gives you all kinds of
benefits outside of just

00:08:56.290 --> 00:08:57.950
you're making money.

00:08:57.950 --> 00:08:59.710
You can also use
that information

00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:01.502
to pitch the folks at
Google and say, look,

00:09:01.502 --> 00:09:03.335
I've got a really good
game here and I think

00:09:03.335 --> 00:09:04.460
you guys should support it.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:05.335
SARAH THOMSON: Right.

00:09:05.335 --> 00:09:06.640
And you just scaled from there?

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:06.820
MIKE GORDON: Yeah.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:07.320
That's it.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:12.230
I mean, on every game we start
really small in open beta.

00:09:12.230 --> 00:09:14.650
I'm predominately
spending my budgets

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:20.660
on Facebook, Unity, Google
Play, AdWords, Tapjoy, and Iron

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:22.650
Source, and some ad action.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:25.060
Those are the big six for me.

00:09:25.060 --> 00:09:27.070
It's a mix of display
and video ads,

00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:28.540
and then as the
game's net revenue

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:32.260
grows we come up with
a monthly budget,

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:35.290
and then we spend that
every month at either net

00:09:35.290 --> 00:09:36.910
neutral or ROI positive.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:38.980
And my games don't
have massive RPUs.

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:43.720
We're talking like $0.50
CPIs for Western users.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:45.800
So it can be done.

00:09:45.800 --> 00:09:46.600
I do it every day.

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:48.250
I did it this morning.

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:50.110
Yeah.

00:09:50.110 --> 00:09:52.820
SARAH THOMSON: And just one
last question around that.

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:54.740
Can you tell me a
little bit about--

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:57.470
you referenced the fact that
things change on the store.

00:09:57.470 --> 00:09:57.970
Right?

00:09:57.970 --> 00:09:58.950
MIKE GORDON: Yeah.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:01.410
SARAH THOMSON: The way
that games are surfaced

00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:04.990
and what's going on behind
the curtain, so to speak,

00:10:04.990 --> 00:10:05.670
is changing.

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:08.220
And that can be
really daunting, I

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:10.670
think, for developers of all
sizes, but especially indies.

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:13.710
So how has that
been to navigate?

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:16.293
What's sort of your
outlook on that?

00:10:16.293 --> 00:10:18.210
MIKE GORDON: My outlook
on it is that you guys

00:10:18.210 --> 00:10:20.820
have a business that you're
optimizing and growing.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:24.510
So I don't begrudge any changes
that happen on the store

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:27.990
because it's something that
Google's heavily invested in,

00:10:27.990 --> 00:10:30.240
and it's their right to do
whatever they want with it,

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:32.680
to grow it and change
it as they see fit.

00:10:32.680 --> 00:10:34.890
The way I feel about it
is that it's terrifying

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:37.620
when users start disappearing.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:39.790
But there's always a signal.

00:10:39.790 --> 00:10:41.220
So I have a broad data set.

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:45.300
I'm a publisher, so I
have 15 games or more.

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:48.720
Whenever anything changes I
dig deep to see who the winners

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.430
and losers were
and try and come up

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:54.190
with a hypothesis as to
why they won or lost.

00:10:54.190 --> 00:10:55.980
But typically
marketing has allowed

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.020
me to weather most storms.

00:10:58.020 --> 00:11:01.310
I think if you have a consistent
stream of marketing, whatever

00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:04.080
is happening with organic
installs on the store,

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:07.440
as long as it's not affecting
that first 30-day window

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:11.760
and it's not punishing
us on the paid

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:15.337
to organic ratio for live games,
you can pretty much weather it.

00:11:15.337 --> 00:11:16.920
You just gotta get
to that point where

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:19.710
you're reinvesting in
marketing on a monthly basis.

00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:22.290
SARAH THOMSON: And I want
to point out and give a plug

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:23.650
for Mike's talk tomorrow.

