Great.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:57.000
MIKE GORDON: Good time.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:58.917
SARAH THOMSON: So let's
jump over to Sam here.

00:11:58.917 --> 00:12:00.315
Thanks, Mike.

00:12:00.315 --> 00:12:03.210
So you guys have been around
for a number of years now,

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:07.830
and doing a pretty good job of
weathering some crazy storms

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:11.170
in the indie world, and
you've seen great success.

00:12:11.170 --> 00:12:12.567
So, what's your secret?

00:12:12.567 --> 00:12:13.900
How have you managed to do that?

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:14.910
SAM COSTER: So I
think it kind of

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:16.577
goes back to what you
were talking about

00:12:16.577 --> 00:12:19.140
as far as the concept of how
do you build a business that

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:22.200
is able to weather the various
changes that are happening

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:23.993
literally all the time.

00:12:23.993 --> 00:12:26.160
So while Mike's taking more
of a marketing approach,

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:27.750
ours has been more on
the community engagement

00:12:27.750 --> 00:12:28.420
side of things.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:31.908
So through that
newsletter system--

00:12:31.908 --> 00:12:33.450
essentially the
first reason we built

00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:34.780
that was because we said, OK.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.930
We can't necessarily
always guarantee

00:12:36.930 --> 00:12:39.060
that Google or Apple
or anybody else

00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:40.390
is going to give us a feature.

00:12:40.390 --> 00:12:40.890
Right?

00:12:40.890 --> 00:12:42.872
It's never guaranteed,
and also they've

00:12:42.872 --> 00:12:44.080
got their own stuff going on.

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:46.380
Maybe Super Mario Run
launches and absorbs

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:48.840
all of the top
spots for something,

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:50.820
or all sorts of games
come out and just start

00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:52.380
absorbing all sorts
of feature spots

00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:54.630
where usually you would
think you'd be in there.

00:12:54.630 --> 00:12:57.900
So we said, how can we
actually robustly build

00:12:57.900 --> 00:12:59.430
a future for
ourselves where we get

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:03.060
to control at least a little
bit of that launch potential,

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:05.070
and actually do it without
any marketing money?

00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:07.140
So we're heavy on the tech side.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:09.120
We build a lot tools
for ourselves and things

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:11.490
like that to really
optimize workflows

00:13:11.490 --> 00:13:14.090
as well as to optimize things
like these sort of marketing

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:15.090
back channels and stuff.

00:13:15.090 --> 00:13:18.000
So for us the answer came
in the form of building

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.520
this proprietary tech,
which really was originally

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:21.510
built in PHP--

00:13:21.510 --> 00:13:24.492
like a really kind of
hideous back end system,

00:13:24.492 --> 00:13:26.450
Which is much better now,
much more stable now.

00:13:26.450 --> 00:13:29.728
But it allowed people to
just back up their data.

00:13:29.728 --> 00:13:30.770
It's a Cloud save system.

00:13:30.770 --> 00:13:31.440
Right?

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:33.480
And because our games
are cross-platform

00:13:33.480 --> 00:13:35.700
that meant that if someone
played it on their tablet

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:37.303
on Android and then
hopped on their PC

00:13:37.303 --> 00:13:39.720
then they could just pick up
exactly where they came from.

00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:41.762
And we found our users
really, really liked that,

00:13:41.762 --> 00:13:44.370
and it also gave them a reason
to give us their email address.

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:45.870
So the question
then is, what do you

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:47.670
do once you have
that email address?

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:49.170
For some reason
indies in particular

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:52.460
really love Twitter,
when Twitter has, like,

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:55.320
the lowest pick-up rate of
almost any communication

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:57.460
channel you could ever
try to broadcast on.

00:13:57.460 --> 00:13:58.350
It's sort of like
you're just kind

00:13:58.350 --> 00:14:00.350
of screaming into the
void a lot, with hashtags.

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:01.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:05.475
And so, I mean, we're talking
between a 15% and 40% open rate

00:14:05.475 --> 00:14:07.350
on these emails that
we're sending to people.

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:09.990
We're sending them to,
like, 150,000 people.

00:14:09.990 --> 00:14:12.900
And what we found over the
years is that everywhere we've

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.000
gone to build an
audience has always

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.380
ended up getting restricted.

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:18.720
So, for example, we first
built an audience on Facebook,

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:21.090
and then it became
quickly clear that if we

00:14:21.090 --> 00:14:23.190
wanted to actually reach
the 20,000 people that we

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:26.030
had driven to that page to
like us through our games,

00:14:26.030 --> 00:14:28.680
that we had to pay money now
to reach the audience that we

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:29.618
had curated there.

00:14:29.618 --> 00:14:32.160
And on Twitter it was the same
thing, where we couldn't quite

00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:34.308
hit our total audience pool.

00:14:34.308 --> 00:14:35.100
And so we said, OK.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:36.725
Email looks like a
good way to do this.

00:14:36.725 --> 00:14:38.910
And for some reason it's
not a tool that indies use.

00:14:38.910 --> 00:14:41.203
So as far as something
that's-- it's a really,

00:14:41.203 --> 00:14:42.120
really effective tool.

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:43.620
And, yes, there are some
complications with something

00:14:43.620 --> 00:14:46.230
like GDPR, but it's actually
not particularly difficult.

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:47.340
It seems really scary.

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:49.590
And it is really easy to
walk through once you get it.

00:14:49.590 --> 00:14:51.640
So the email newsletter system.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:54.240
And then on top of that,
we do a weekly podcast,

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:55.717
which is just us--

00:14:55.717 --> 00:14:58.050
me and my two brothers-- just
getting a room for an hour

00:14:58.050 --> 00:15:00.115
and basically being weirdos.

00:15:00.115 --> 00:15:01.490
We talk about the
games industry,

00:15:01.490 --> 00:15:02.790
we talk about the
game we're working on,

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:04.415
and then we answer
community questions.

00:15:04.415 --> 00:15:07.610
And we-- depending
on the week-- will

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:11.910
have around between 1,500
and 2,500 listeners per week.

00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:15.650
And if you talk about the
power of having your fan base

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:18.930
listen to you talk for
an hour every week--

00:15:18.930 --> 00:15:20.890
that's something that
really can't be matched.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:26.180
And cumulatively the podcast
has had over 350,000 hours

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:27.630
of people listening.

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:28.130
Right?

00:15:28.130 --> 00:15:30.470
And so it's allowed us
to build a fan base,

00:15:30.470 --> 00:15:32.780
even start a little tiny
mini convention of our own

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:35.120
in St. Lewis where we're
based in the Midwest,

00:15:35.120 --> 00:15:38.270
that people flew from
Florida and drove from Texas

00:15:38.270 --> 00:15:39.053
to come see us.

00:15:39.053 --> 00:15:40.970
So it's allowed us to
do a lot of these things

00:15:40.970 --> 00:15:43.140
that normally we would
feel very out of reach for,

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:45.680
and in a lot of ways weather
all these changes long

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:47.240
enough that we can
pivot effectively

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:49.580
and take advantage of whatever
the new sort of shiny thing

00:15:49.580 --> 00:15:50.570
is that we're supposed to do.

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.195
SARAH THOMSON: So
was that intentional,

00:15:52.195 --> 00:15:57.780
to build your fan base
around your studio brand

00:15:57.780 --> 00:15:58.595
as opposed to--

00:15:58.595 --> 00:15:58.760
SAM COSTER: Yes.

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:00.927
SARAH THOMSON: And then,
of course, it cascades down

00:16:00.927 --> 00:16:01.940
into the gaming brands.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:04.530
But was that an intentional
thing or did you just get

00:16:04.530 --> 00:16:05.030
lucky?

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:05.180
SAM COSTER: Absolutely.

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:05.950
Yeah.

00:16:05.950 --> 00:16:07.910
Well, do I think it's
absolutely intentional?

00:16:07.910 --> 00:16:09.452
And definitely luck
is involved, too.

00:16:09.452 --> 00:16:12.110
So a big part of
it was recognizing

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:13.760
that we were tired of--

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:15.710
so basically we had
launched these four games

00:16:15.710 --> 00:16:16.880
within two years or so.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:19.790
And these were smaller,
strictly mobile titles.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:22.820
And doing the run-up every
single time to launch

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:24.985
was always so harrowing
because you're like,

00:16:24.985 --> 00:16:26.360
are we-- we're
talking to Google.

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:27.450
Are we going to get
a feature in there?

00:16:27.450 --> 00:16:28.285
Like, I don't know.

00:16:28.285 --> 00:16:28.785
Maybe.

00:16:28.785 --> 00:16:29.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.760
And then we don't have money to
spend on ads, so we're like--

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:33.230
MIKE GORDON: You and I
both know that's not how

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:34.250
that happened on Crashlands.

00:16:34.250 --> 00:16:34.430
SAM COSTER: Well,
not on Crashlands.

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:35.280
MIKE GORDON: Am I
going to get a feature?

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:35.780
Yes.

00:16:35.780 --> 00:16:36.604
SAM COSTER: Crashlands will.

00:16:36.604 --> 00:16:37.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:37.430 --> 00:16:40.280
So the previous
four, not so much.

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:40.820
So, yeah.

00:16:40.820 --> 00:16:44.030
So a big part of that
then was just saying,

00:16:44.030 --> 00:16:48.530
how can we take a single
player coming into Crashlands

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:50.750
or into Flop Rocket--
one of our other games--

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:52.852
and how can we get them
excited about the breadth

00:16:52.852 --> 00:16:54.060
of all the rest of our games?

00:16:54.060 --> 00:16:55.040
So all of our
games actually take

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:56.290
place in the same universe.

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:58.290
They have the same art
style across all of them,

00:16:58.290 --> 00:16:59.090
no matter what the genre is.

00:16:59.090 --> 00:17:01.100
And they hop around
genres all over the place,

00:17:01.100 --> 00:17:02.540
from things that
make you want to snap

00:17:02.540 --> 00:17:03.915
your phone in half
to Crashlands,

00:17:03.915 --> 00:17:05.480
which is like a 60-hour RPG.

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:09.472
So a big part of it was,
yeah, this really intentional,

00:17:09.472 --> 00:17:11.180
how do we get someone
to come in and then

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:14.530
stay with us as a team as
opposed to just saying,

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:15.880
I really like that game.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:17.630
I've no idea who made
it and I don't care.

00:17:17.630 --> 00:17:18.020
SARAH THOMSON: Yeah.

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:18.920
That's awesome.

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:20.730
So we're almost
out of time here,

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:23.390
and I really want to know--

00:17:23.390 --> 00:17:26.810
obviously you and your brothers
have a particular talent

00:17:26.810 --> 00:17:29.750
of that kind of
community-building effort

00:17:29.750 --> 00:17:30.800
around the podcast.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:34.063
And there's charisma and
personality happening there,

00:17:34.063 --> 00:17:35.730
and not all of us are
blessed with that.

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:36.438
SAM COSTER: Sure.

00:17:36.438 --> 00:17:39.680
SARAH THOMSON: So how
can you, as a very small,

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:45.242
resource-limited team, build
a community in different ways?

00:17:45.242 --> 00:17:45.950
SAM COSTER: Yeah.

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:47.825
I mean, honestly I think
the highest leverage

00:17:47.825 --> 00:17:50.180
way to do it is through
something like a newsletter.

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:50.960
SARAH THOMSON: OK.

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:52.130
SAM COSTER: A lot of people--

00:17:52.130 --> 00:17:54.630
especially if you're an indie
or you just like making games,

00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:56.620
a lot of people are more
introverted by nature.

00:17:56.620 --> 00:17:58.100
And I do actually consider
myself an introvert,

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:00.100
I'm just good at
talking when I need to.

00:18:00.100 --> 00:18:02.720
But I think everybody
usually has the ability

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:03.898
to write pretty effectively.

00:18:03.898 --> 00:18:05.690
And you should actually
develop that skill.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:08.232
And that's something that you
can do sort of on your own time

00:18:08.232 --> 00:18:10.820
without the pressure
of an instant response.

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:13.980
And those email newsletters
are honestly so phenomenal.

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:16.520
I know there's a talk
about Chris Zukowski

00:18:16.520 --> 00:18:19.325
about this exact topic,
I think, tomorrow,

00:18:19.325 --> 00:18:21.200
which is all about how
to build an email list

00:18:21.200 --> 00:18:22.530
and then use it
really effectively.

00:18:22.530 --> 00:18:24.260
And it's one of those things
that, for some reason,

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:24.843
people ignore.

00:18:24.843 --> 00:18:26.940
Kind of like the user
acquisition side on indies.

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:29.060
And it can help
you so much, even

00:18:29.060 --> 00:18:30.470
if it's just like 2000 people.

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:32.540
Or even-- like, we started
ours with 13 people.

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:34.110
So, you know, it
takes a little bit.

00:18:34.110 --> 00:18:34.610
Then you go.

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:36.858
MIKE GORDON: Do you guys
do any incentivization

00:18:36.858 --> 00:18:38.150
in the actual games themselves?

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:39.200
Do you, like, get
this cool thing--

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:39.520
SAM COSTER: Yeah.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:41.000
That's where, essentially,
the Cloud saving--

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.440
all those additional
features come from.

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:43.190
And we do cross-game--

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:43.980
MIKE GORDON: All
packaged together.

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:44.840
SAM COSTER: All
packaged together.

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:46.852
We do cross-game
unlocks and stuff, too.

00:18:46.852 --> 00:18:48.560
So if you beat a boss
in one of our games

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:50.840
it will unlock a quest
line in Crashlands

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:52.180
when you're playing, as long
as you're on the same account.

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:54.360
So all sorts of crazy
tech stuff like that.

00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:55.010
MIKE GORDON: That's cool.

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:55.830
SARAH THOMSON: That's awesome.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:57.450
So we're going to
end on that note.

00:18:57.450 --> 00:18:58.130
Thanks, guys.

00:18:58.130 --> 00:19:00.170
This is huge gems
of wisdom you're

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:01.670
able to share with
this audience.

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:03.650
And thank you so much.

